<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>Cobalt Strike: Favorite Tool from APT to Crimeware </span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2021-06-29T20:27:16Z">June 29, 2021</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                Selena Larson and Daniel Blackford
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <pre>
<em>(Updated 8/18/2021 at the request of a third-party)</em></pre>

<h3>Key Findings&nbsp;</h3>

<ul>
	<li>Malicious use of Cobalt Strike&nbsp;in threat actor campaigns&nbsp;is increasing.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Threat actor use of Cobalt Strike increased 161 percent&nbsp;from 2019 to&nbsp;2020&nbsp;and remains&nbsp;a&nbsp;high-volume&nbsp;threat&nbsp;in 2021.&nbsp;</li>
	<li>Cobalt Strike is&nbsp;currently&nbsp;used by more cybercrime and general commodity <a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/threat-reference/malware">malware</a> operators than APT and espionage threat actors.&nbsp;</li>
</ul>

<h3>Overview&nbsp;</h3>

<p>In 2021, Cobalt Strike&nbsp;is&nbsp;appearing&nbsp;in&nbsp;Proofpoint&nbsp;threat&nbsp;data more frequently than ever.&nbsp;Cobalt Strike is a legitimate security tool used by penetration testers to emulate&nbsp;threat actor&nbsp;activity in a network. However, it is&nbsp;also&nbsp;increasingly used by malicious actors – Proofpoint saw a 161 percent increase in threat actor use of the tool&nbsp;from&nbsp;2019&nbsp;to&nbsp;2020.&nbsp;This aligns with&nbsp;<a href="https://www.recordedfuture.com/2020-adversary-infrastructure-report/" rel="noreferrer noopener">observations</a>&nbsp;from other security firms as more threat actors adopt hacking tools in their operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>When&nbsp;mapped to&nbsp;the&nbsp;<a href="https://attack.mitre.org/matrices/enterprise/" rel="noreferrer noopener">MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework</a>, Proofpoint’s&nbsp;visibility&nbsp;into the attack chain&nbsp;focuses on&nbsp;<a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/threat-insight/first-step-initial-access-leads-ransomware">Initial Access</a>, Execution, and Persistence&nbsp;mechanisms.&nbsp;That is: How are threat actors attempting to compromise hosts and what payloads are they deploying first?&nbsp;Our&nbsp;corpus of&nbsp;threat actor&nbsp;data includes&nbsp;criminal&nbsp;and state-associated&nbsp;threat actor&nbsp;groups.&nbsp;Based on our data,&nbsp;Proofpoint assesses&nbsp;with high confidence&nbsp;that&nbsp;Cobalt Strike is becoming increasingly popular among threat actors as an initial access payload, not just a second-stage&nbsp;tool threat actors&nbsp;use&nbsp;once access is achieved, with&nbsp;criminal&nbsp;threat&nbsp;actors making up the bulk of&nbsp;attributed&nbsp;Cobalt Strike&nbsp;campaigns&nbsp;in 2020.&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Background&nbsp;</h3>

<p>In December 2020, the world learned about an expansive and effective espionage campaign that successfully backdoored the popular network monitoring software SolarWinds. Investigators&nbsp;<a href="https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2020/12/evasive-attacker-leverages-solarwinds-supply-chain-compromises-with-sunburst-backdoor.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">revealed tools&nbsp;</a>used by the threat actors included Cobalt Strike Beacon. This campaign was attributed to threat actors working for Russia’s Foreign Intelligence Service – a group with Cobalt Strike in their toolbox&nbsp;<a href="https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2018/11/not-so-cozy-an-uncomfortable-examination-of-a-suspected-apt29-phishing-campaign.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">since at least</a>&nbsp;2018. This high-profile activity was part of a clever attack chain enabling advanced threat actors to surreptitiously compromise a relatively small number of victims.&nbsp;The tool used, and customized to fit their needs,&nbsp;is almost a decade old but increasingly popular.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Cobalt Strike&nbsp;<a href="https://blog.cobaltstrike.com/2016/03/02/a-history-of-cobalt-strike-in-training-courses/" rel="noreferrer noopener">debuted</a>&nbsp;in 2012 in response to perceived gaps in&nbsp;an existing red team tool, the Metasploit Framework.&nbsp;In 2015, Cobalt Strike 3.0 launched as a standalone adversary emulation platform. By 2016,&nbsp;Proofpoint&nbsp;researchers&nbsp;began observing threat actors using Cobalt Strike.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Historically,&nbsp;Cobalt Strike use in malicious operations was largely&nbsp;associated with&nbsp;well-resourced threat actors,&nbsp;including&nbsp;<a href="https://community.broadcom.com/symantecenterprise/communities/community-home/librarydocuments/viewdocument?DocumentKey=257dd693-5986-41bf-bc33-f9dc76d9c6a8&amp;CommunityKey=1ecf5f55-9545-44d6-b0f4-4e4a7f5f5e68&amp;tab=librarydocuments" rel="noreferrer noopener">large cybercrime&nbsp;operators</a>&nbsp;like&nbsp;TA3546&nbsp;(also known as FIN7), and advanced persistent threat (APT)&nbsp;<a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/threat-insight/post/leviathan-espionage-actor-spearphishes-maritime-and-defense-targets" rel="noreferrer noopener">groups&nbsp;such as TA423</a>&nbsp;(also known as Leviathan&nbsp;or APT40).&nbsp;Proofpoint researchers have&nbsp;attributed two-thirds of&nbsp;identified&nbsp;Cobalt Strike campaigns&nbsp;from 2016 through 2018 to&nbsp;well-resourced&nbsp;cybercrime organizations or APT groups.&nbsp;That ratio decreased&nbsp;dramatically the following years&nbsp;– between 2019 and present, just 15&nbsp;percent&nbsp;of Cobalt Strike campaigns&nbsp;were&nbsp;attributable to known threat actors.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p><img alt="Chart, line chart

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Figure 1: Number of email messages associated with a Cobalt Strike payload observed over&nbsp;time.&nbsp;Note: 2021 figures include data through May&nbsp;2021.&nbsp;</em></p>

<p>Threat actors&nbsp;can obtain Cobalt Strike in a variety of ways:&nbsp;purchasing it directly from the&nbsp;vendor’s&nbsp;website, which requires verification;&nbsp;buying&nbsp;a version&nbsp;on the dark web&nbsp;via&nbsp;various hacking forums;&nbsp;or using cracked, illegitimate&nbsp;versions of the software.&nbsp;In March 2020, a cracked version&nbsp;of Cobalt Strike 4.0 was released&nbsp;and made available to threat actors.&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Cobalt Strike’s Appeal&nbsp;</h3>

<p>Cobalt Strike is used by a diverse array of threat actors, and while it&nbsp;is not unusual for cybercriminal and APT actors to leverage similar tooling in their campaigns, Cobalt Strike is unique in&nbsp;that&nbsp;&nbsp;its&nbsp;built-in capabilities&nbsp;enable it to&nbsp;be quickly deployed and operationalized regardless of actor sophistication or access to human or financial resources.&nbsp;The job of simulating actor attacks and penetrating defenses might become a bit more straightforward when both sides are using the same tool.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p lang="EN-US">Cobalt Strike is also&nbsp;session-based — that is, if threat actors can access a host and complete an operation without needing to establish ongoing persistence, there will not be remaining artifacts on the host after it is no longer running in-memory. In essence: they can hit it and forget it.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Threat actors can also use the malleability of Cobalt Strike to create customized builds that add or remove features to achieve objectives or evade detection. For example, APT29 frequently uses custom Cobalt Strike Beacon loaders to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2018/11/not-so-cozy-an-uncomfortable-examination-of-a-suspected-apt29-phishing-campaign.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">blend in</a>&nbsp;with legitimate traffic or&nbsp;<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2021/05/28/breaking-down-nobeliums-latest-early-stage-toolset/" rel="noreferrer noopener">evade analysis</a>.&nbsp;</p>

<p lang="EN-US">&nbsp;For defenders,&nbsp;customized Cobalt Strike modules often require unique signatures, so threat detection engineers may be required to play catch-up to Cobalt Strike use in the wild.&nbsp;Cobalt Strike&nbsp;is also&nbsp;appealing to threat actors&nbsp;for&nbsp;its inherent obfuscation. Attribution gets more difficult if everyone is using the same tool.&nbsp;If&nbsp;an organization has&nbsp;a red team actively making use of it, it&nbsp;is possible malicious traffic could be mistaken as legitimate.&nbsp;The&nbsp;software’s&nbsp;ease&nbsp;of use&nbsp;can improve&nbsp;the&nbsp;capabilities&nbsp;of less sophisticated actors.&nbsp;For sophisticated actors, why spend development cycles on something&nbsp;new&nbsp;when you already have a great tool for the job?&nbsp;</p>

<p>Proofpoint data shows&nbsp;Cobalt Strike is a&nbsp;popular tool&nbsp;for everything from strategic compromises to noisy, widespread campaigns.&nbsp;The following examples illustrate a small sampling of the types of threat actors leveraging Cobalt Strike&nbsp;tracked by&nbsp;Proofpoint.&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Threat Actors&nbsp;</h3>

<p><strong>TA800</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p>TA800 is a large&nbsp;crimeware&nbsp;group tracked by Proofpoint since&nbsp;mid-2019. This actor attempts to deliver and install banking malware or malware loaders, including&nbsp;The Trick and&nbsp;BazaLoader.&nbsp;In April 2020, TA800 became the first group observed distributing&nbsp;BazaLoader.&nbsp;In these early campaigns, the&nbsp;threat actor distributed emails with a malicious link to an executable or a landing page hosted on Google Docs with a link to an executable. The executable downloaded the&nbsp;BazaLoader&nbsp;backdoor which in turn downloaded Cobalt Strike.&nbsp;In February 2021, the group pivoted to distributing Cobalt Strike as a first-stage payload via malicious URLs.&nbsp;There has been some evidence suggesting TA800’s&nbsp;<a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/threat-insight/nimzaloader-ta800s-new-initial-access-malware" rel="noreferrer noopener">NimzaLoader </a>is being used to download and execute Cobalt Strike as its secondary payload.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>TA547</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p>TA547 is&nbsp;a&nbsp;crimeware&nbsp;actor tracked by Proofpoint since October 2017. This group appears to be interested in distributing primarily banking trojans – including&nbsp;The&nbsp;Trick and&nbsp;ZLoader&nbsp;– to various geographic&nbsp;regions.&nbsp;Since mid-2020, this actor favors using malicious Microsoft&nbsp;Office&nbsp;attachments to distribute&nbsp;malware. In February 2021, TA547&nbsp;began distributing Cobalt Strike as a second-stage payload for command and control.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>TA415</strong>&nbsp;</p>

<p>TA415 is an&nbsp;APT&nbsp;actor&nbsp;believed to be associated with&nbsp;People’s Republic of China&nbsp;(PRC)&nbsp;state interests.&nbsp;The group has been noted in United States court filings to be tied to PRC’s Ministry of State Security.&nbsp;TA415 is also known as Barium&nbsp;and APT41.&nbsp;Proofpoint identified TA415&nbsp;delivering Cobalt Strike as a first-stage payload&nbsp;in limited campaigns during mid-2020. In September 2020, the United States Department of Justice announced the indictment of several threat actors associated with this threat group, and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/seven-international-cyber-defendants-including-apt41-actors-charged-connection-computer" rel="noreferrer noopener">detailed</a>&nbsp;the threat actors use of Cobalt Strike in&nbsp;the&nbsp;indictment.&nbsp;Based on recent&nbsp;<a href="https://blog.group-ib.com/colunmtk_apt41" target="_blank">reporting by Group-IB</a>,&nbsp;TA415&nbsp;used&nbsp;Cobalt Strike in a campaign against an entity in the airlines sector.</p>

<p>The following timeline provides&nbsp;a small sample of&nbsp;threat actor use of Cobalt Strike across cybercrime and APT threats. The&nbsp;selected&nbsp;events&nbsp;were identified based on their significance, and&nbsp;are not representative of the full Cobalt Strike threat landscape.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{2ab64e5c-7243-4adc-9c81-b19597615f8f}{50}" paraid="80330015"><img alt="Timeline

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Figure 2: Timeline of threats using Cobalt Strike.&nbsp;Links to the sources are available in the References section.&nbsp;</em></p>

<h3>Attack Chain&nbsp;</h3>

<p>Proofpoint has observed dozens of threat actors using Cobalt Strike.&nbsp;However,&nbsp;like their legitimate counterparts, threat actors exhibit many attack paths and use cases of the&nbsp;malicious actor&nbsp;emulation software. Threat actors use different lure themes, threat types, droppers, and payloads. For example, the earliest Cobalt Strike campaigns distributed email threats with malicious document attachments to distribute the malware, but campaigns distributing malicious URLs directly in the email body have overtaken attachments as the more frequently utilized threat type.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>While instances of Cobalt Strike being sent directly as an initial payload have dramatically increased, deployment as a second stage payload remains popular. Cobalt Strike has been observed in a variety of attack chains alongside malware such as The Trick,&nbsp;BazaLoader,&nbsp;Ursnif,&nbsp;IcedID, and many more popular loaders. In these cases, the preceding malware typically loads and executes Cobalt Strike. Likewise, there is a wide array of techniques leveraged in cases where Cobalt Strike is delivered directly, such as via malicious macros in weaponized Office documents, compressed executables, PowerShell, dynamic data exchange (DDE), HTA/HTML files, and traffic distribution systems.&nbsp;</p>

<p>After Cobalt Strike has been executed and a&nbsp;Beacon established&nbsp;for C2 communication, actors have been observed attempting to enumerate network connections and dumping Active Directory credentials as they try to move laterally to a network resource such as a Domain Controller, allowing for deployment of ransomware to all networked systems. For example, the Cobalt Strike&nbsp;<a href="https://www.cobaltstrike.com/help-beacon" rel="noreferrer noopener">documentation states</a>:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Use the net&nbsp;dclist&nbsp;command to find the&nbsp;Domain&nbsp;Controller for the domain the target is joined to. Use the&nbsp;net view&nbsp;command to find targets on the domain the target is joined to.&nbsp;</p>

<p>In addition to network discovery and credential dumping, Cobalt Strike Beacon also has the capability to elevate privileges, load and execute additional tools, and to inject these functions into existing running host processes to attempt to avoid detection.&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Outlook&nbsp;</h3>

<p>Proofpoint researchers anticipate Cobalt Strike will continue to be a commonly used tool in threat actor toolsets. According to internal data,&nbsp;tens of thousands of&nbsp;organizations&nbsp;have already been targeted&nbsp;with&nbsp;Cobalt Strike, based on observed campaigns.&nbsp;We expect this number to increase in 2021.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;<img alt="Chart type: Line. TOTAL_CUST increases over time.

Description automatically generated" src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Figure 3: Number of customers targeted by threats using Cobalt Strike&nbsp;</em></p>

<h3>Conclusion&nbsp;</h3>

<p>Cobalt Strike is a useful tool, for legitimate security researchers and threat actors alike. Its malleability coupled with&nbsp;its usability makes it a robust and effective tool for siphoning data, moving laterally, and&nbsp;loading additional malware payloads.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Cobalt Strike is not the only red team tool appearing more often in&nbsp;Proofpoint&nbsp;data. Others include Mythic, Meterpreter, and the Veil Framework.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>The use of publicly available tooling aligns with a broader trend observed by Proofpoint: Threat actors are using as many legitimate tools as possible, including executing Windows processes like PowerShell and WMI; injecting malicious code into legitimate binaries; and frequently using allowable services like Dropbox, Google Drive, SendGrid, and Constant Contact to host and distribute malware. &nbsp;</p>

<p>The following references are associated with the above timeline.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>October 2017 –&nbsp;<a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/threat-insight/post/leviathan-espionage-actor-spearphishes-maritime-and-defense-targets" rel="noreferrer noopener">Leviathan: Espionage actor&nbsp;spearphishes&nbsp;maritime and defense targets</a>&nbsp;</p>

<p>December 2020 –&nbsp;<a href="https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2020/12/evasive-attacker-leverages-solarwinds-supply-chain-compromises-with-sunburst-backdoor.html" rel="noreferrer noopener">Highly Evasive Attacker Leverages SolarWinds Supply Chain to Compromise Multiple Global Victims With SUNBURST Backdoor</a>&nbsp;</p>

<p>May 2021 –&nbsp;<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/security/blog/2021/05/27/new-sophisticated-email-based-attack-from-nobelium/" rel="noreferrer noopener">New sophisticated email-based attack from NOBELIUM</a>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h4>Detections&nbsp;</h4>

<p>Proofpoint Emerging Threats includes robust detections for Cobalt Strike. The following are a sample of our detections as they relate to the behaviors described in this report.&nbsp;</p>

<p>2028591 ET TROJAN&nbsp;Cobalt Strike Malleable C2 Request YouTube Profile&nbsp;</p>

<p>2028589 ET TROJAN&nbsp;Cobalt Strike Malleable C2 Response O365 Profile M2&nbsp;</p>

<p>2032749 ET TROJAN&nbsp;Cobalt&nbsp;Strike Malleable C2 Amazon Profile&nbsp;</p>

<p>2032746 ET TROJAN&nbsp;Cobalt&nbsp;Strike Malleable C2&nbsp;QiHoo&nbsp;Profile&nbsp;</p>

<p>2027082 ET TROJAN Observed Malicious SSL Cert&nbsp;CobaltStrike&nbsp;C2&nbsp;</p>

<p>2023629 ET INFO Suspicious Empty SSL Certificate - Observed in Cobalt Strike&nbsp;</p>

<p>2032362 ET TROJAN Cobalt Strike Beacon Activity&nbsp;</p>
